english:
  title: 'Stele Inscription and Preface for Master Lee, Posthumously Honored as Lord of Seowon: Minister of the Right in the Chancellery, and Court Gentleman for Ceremonial Matters'
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the eighth month of the first year of Yongle, the Director of the Office of State Affairs and Lord of Seowon, Master Lee, entrusted me with composing an inscription for his ancestor's tomb and spoke thus: "My late father sowed virtue without harvesting its fruits, and left this legacy for us, his descendants. Through his benevolence, my father and I have received the favor and honor of the throne, our rank elevated and our stipends enriched. The throne granted posthumous honors to our ancestors and we burned the ritual papers to offer sacrifices, thereby illuminating the imperial grace. Yet his tomb lacks an inscription, leaving no way to demonstrate his virtue to posterity. Moreover, I was unfortunate to lose my father in childhood, and my three elder brothers have all passed before me. I cannot fully recount the moral conduct of my ancestors, and I fear their memory may fade and be lost. Could you not examine our genealogy and official records, and compose an inscription for us?"

    I could not refuse. Upon investigation, I find that the Lee clan hails from Cheongju and is among the most renowned and enduring families of the realm. When the founder of Goryeo rose to establish his dynasty, there was an ancestor named Neung-hui who rendered service to the king and was enfeoffed as a National Duke, his portrait displayed among the meritorious officials on the palace wall. Six generations later came an ancestor named Gong-seung, whose conduct was pure and whose virtue was manifest. He served both King In and King Yi with distinction, and was once sent as an envoy to the Jin, yet accepted not a single coin. His pristine virtue thus became legendary. King Yi, gazing at the moon on an autumn evening when the sky was clear and cloudless, marveled at its radiance for a long time and said: "This bright moon tonight resembles Master Gong-seung's heart—not a speck of dust mars its surface." At his passing, he was granted the posthumous name Mun-jeong, the Pure Exemplar.

    Through centuries thus, his descendants have upheld his legacy, each generation cultivating virtue and passing it forward. By the time of Master Mun-gan, the virtue of our ancestors had grown still stronger. He refined himself ever more, bestowing blessings upon his descendants. The Director and his son, the Lord of Sangdang, united their hearts and exerted all their strength in service to our Joseon, winning merit as founding supporters of the dynasty. Both were enrolled among the meritorious officials and elevated to the highest offices. The Lord of Sangdang and his younger brother, the Lord of Cheongpyeong, both married princesses of the realm. The blessings of accumulated virtue thus grew ever greater and more abundant. Ah, how magnificent this flourishing!

    Master Mun-gan bore the name Jeong, known in his youth as Chun-gil. In the year Eul-chuk of the Tae-jeong era, when he was twenty-nine, he first received appointment through the hereditary privilege as Judge of the Eight Pavilions. The following winter he passed the civil service examination, placing second in the third rank. He rose through the ranks from Gentleman of the Carriage to various judicial posts. In the first year of Chi-hwa, as an official of the Ministry of Records, he was sent to govern Chogye District with beneficent administration. Later he served in the Censorate, held the position of Director of Scrutiny and Investigation, and was appointed Inspector of Gyeongsang Province. After ten years of retirement in Jinju at Sangsan Mountain, living in leisure and tranquility, he again served as Rector of the National Academy and Grand Keeper of Rites. Through various appointments his ranks advanced, until in the year Mu-sul he became Minister of Personnel and Minister of Justice. His is a record of long and varied service.

    Master maintained a pure and frugal demeanor throughout his life, adhering strictly to propriety and refusing to bend to worldly fashion. The common people revered his integrity and uprightness. He withdrew to Sangsan Mountain in Jinju, seeking neither advancement nor distinction. When Prince Gongmin held the position of heir apparent, he long heard tales of the Master's virtue. Upon ascending the throne, the king summoned him to the capital, admiring his purity and prudence. The king entrusted him with the management of the Inner Buddhist Hall and himself wrote out in his own hand the deeds and exemplary conduct of Master Mun-jeong, as well as the words King Yi spoke when gazing at the moon: "This bright moon tonight is like Master Gong-seung's heart—without a speck of dust." Following this, the king added several hundred words extolling the Master's noble aspirations toward his ancestors and his disdain for the vulgarities of the world, intending to advance him to great responsibility. But suddenly the Master withdrew to his former refuge. On the nineteenth day of the sixth month in the year Sin-chuk, he passed away from illness at the age of sixty-three. He was buried on the southern slope of Sangsan Mountain.

    His father bore the name Gye-gam, was enfeoffed as Lord of Langseong with rank as Grand Counselor, and received the posthumous name Jeong-heon. His grandfather, named Chang-u, held the rank of General Supervisor of the Ministry of Records and was posthumously honored as Commissioner of the Chancellery. His great-grandfather, named Jang, held the rank of Court Attendant and was posthumously honored as Minister of the Chancellery. He was the son of Master Mun-jeong's son, the Vice Premier, named Chun-no. The maternal grandfather was Kim Byeop, honored with the posthumous name Mun-sin, and came from Myeongju. His wife was of the Kim clan of Myeongju, daughter of the official Gye-cho. She lived seventy years and passed away fifteen years after the Master, on the twenty-first day of the fourth month in the year Eul-myo of the Hongwu reign, and was buried beside her husband. Some twenty years later, in recognition of the Director's merit, the Master received the posthumous honor of Minister of the Right and Lord of Seowon, and his wife was enfeoffed as Lady of the Han Kingdom—a bestowing of imperial favor upon the family.

    There were four sons and two daughters. The eldest son, named Yu-sin, passed the civil examination in the year Im-o and served as Commissioner investigating Gyeongsang Province, though he predeceased his father. The second son, named Geo-in, held the rank of Vice Premier and received the posthumous name Gong-jeol. The third son, named Geo-ui, served as Minister of Public Works but died young. The fourth son, named Geo-i, became Vice Premier of the Chancellery and now serves as Director of the Office of State Affairs and Lord of Seowon. The eldest daughter married the Vice Minister Lee Sung, and the second daughter married the Governor Mun Gyeong-saeng. There are numerous grandchildren.

    The second son's offspring were many. His eldest grandson, named Deok-yun, serves as Commandant. The second grandson, named Buk-yun, holds rank as Court Attendant. The eldest granddaughter married Vice Minister Lee Ji, and the second married General Kim So. The third son by his first wife had two young sons. Upon remarriage to the daughter of Lord Lee of Hansan, he fathered a son named Hong-do, who serves as Assistant Director of the Water Ministry. His daughters married various officials of note.

    Through the generosity of the throne, honors were extended to all. The Director's son, named Jeo, became Vice Premier and Lord of Sangdang, marrying the Princess Gyeongsin. His brothers likewise received honors and married into the royal house. The Lord of Cheongpyeong married the Princess Jeongsin. Thus the family's glory expanded with each generation, filling the realm.

    Since ancient times, families with great merit have often declined within a few generations, becoming obscure. This occurs because though ancestors may diligently accumulate virtue, their descendants often grow proud and extravagant, lacking the discipline to maintain their inheritance. Yet this family of Lee has shown that virtue flows from one generation to the next when descendants remain humble and vigilant. The Director and his son have both shown such virtue—respectful, cautious, and ever strengthening their resolve. They do not flaunt their status nor grow arrogant. They pursue goodness tirelessly. Thus they preserve and amplify the splendor of their ancestors, and their blessings shall continue to flow to their descendants without cease.

    Therefore, this inscription is fitting:

    In fertile Seowon, deep and wide,
    Who opened forth this noble spring?
    The National Duke laid the foundation,
    And firmly fixed the family's root.
    That root, established strong,
    Did spread its branches far and wide.
    Master Mun-jeong, great and luminous,
    Whose bearing showed such purity,
    His heart without a speck of dust—
    Clear as the autumn moon.

    Master Mun-gan, bright and faithful,
    Virtuous in all his ways,
    Held fast to propriety's path,
    Never bending to the world's decay.
    Cleanest in his frugal heart,
    He built a deep foundation of grace.
    Fit for the highest office,
    Yet he chose to serve in shade,
    Leaving blessings to his sons,
    Abundance flowing to their days.

    The Director rose with strength and power,
    His loyalty to realm and throne,
    His merit etched in sacred bonds.
    Father and son twice sworn their oaths,
    Together served the kingdom's cause.
    Brothers brilliant, each at court,
    Wedded to the royal line,
    Such resplendent favor fell—
    Rare in ancient ages past.
    All preserve what they have gained,
    Tending well the family way.
    Blessing shall not cease to flow,
    And former glory shine more bright.
    Generation follows generation still,
    The chain unbroken, flowing on.
    Upon this stone the tale is carved,
    For all the ages yet to come.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Eight Pavilions (八關寶) refers to a high-ranking civil position in the Yuan bureaucracy, held through inheritance privilege.
  - key: ''
    value: King Yi's remarks on the autumn moon became a celebrated metaphor in Korean tradition for spiritual purity and freedom from worldly attachments.
  - key: ''
    value: The practice of burning ritual papers (焚黃) was part of Confucian ancestral veneration, ensuring posthumous honors reached the deceased.
  - key: ''
    value: Posthumous honors (posthumous titles and ranks) extended to ancestors recognized the family's contributions across generations, a mark of imperial favor.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to being 'enrolled among meritorious officials' and 'sworn in the covenant' reflects the establishment of the founding families of the Joseon dynasty.
